<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>17924</anchor> <rss>jms-0051.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Observation</taxon> <addr>jms-0051</addr>  <route>jms-0051.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>An alternative definition of duploids</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Equivalently, we can define a <link href="jms-0050.xml" type="local" addr="jms-0050" title="Duploid">duploid</link> to be a <link href="jms-004T.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004T" title="Univalent deductive system">univalent</link> <link href="jms-004F.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004F" title="Preduploid">preduploid</link> such that every object is <em>merely equipped with</em> both an <link href="jms-004M.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004M" title="Upshift structure">upshift</link> and a <link href="jms-004P.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004P" title="Downshift structure">downshift</link>.</p><p>To see that the <link href="jms-0050.xml" type="local" addr="jms-0050" title="Duploid">main definition</link> implies our alternative definition, let <tex>A</tex> be an object of the preduploid; because we are proving that <tex>A</tex> is <em>merely equipped with</em> both an <link href="jms-004M.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004M" title="Upshift structure">upshift</link> and a <link href="jms-004P.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004P" title="Downshift structure">downshift</link>, we may proceed by cases on the <link href="jms-0045.xml" type="local" addr="jms-0045" title="Polarized object">polarization</link> of <tex>A</tex>.</p><ol><li>If <tex>A</tex> is <link href="jms-004B.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004B" title="Positive and negative objects">positive</link>, we choose the identity map <tex>A \vdash  A</tex> for the downshift and we use our assumption to deduce that <tex>A</tex> has an upshift.</li>
  <li>If <tex>A</tex> is <link href="jms-004B.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004B" title="Positive and negative objects">negative</link>, we choose the identity map <tex>A \vdash  A</tex> for the upshift and we use our assumption to deduce that <tex>A</tex> has a downshift.</li></ol>
 
   
   <tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="false" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>17925</anchor> <rss>anon.192.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Proof</taxon> <addr>anon.192</addr>  <route>anon.192.xml</route>    </frontmatter> <mainmatter>
  <p>Conversely, assume that every object is merely equipped with both an upshift and a downshift. That a positive object <tex>P</tex> has an upshift <link href="jms-004X.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004X" title="Uniqueness of upshifts">is a proposition</link>, so we can use our assumption that <tex>P</tex> <em>merely</em> has an upshift. That a negative object <tex>N</tex> has a downshift <link href="jms-004Z.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004Z" title="Uniqueness of downshifts">is likewise a proposition</link>, so we can use our assumption that <tex>N</tex> <em>merely</em> has a downshift.</p>
</mainmatter> </tree>
 
</mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>17926</anchor> <rss>jms-004E.rss.xml</rss>  <addr>jms-004E</addr>  <route>jms-004E.xml</route> <date><year>2022</year> <month>12</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Polarization, preduploids, and duploids</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>17927</anchor> <rss>jms-0045.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-0045</addr>  <route>jms-0045.xml</route> <date><year>2022</year> <month>12</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Polarized object</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>An object <tex>A</tex> in a deductive system is called <em>polarized</em> when it is either <link href="jms-004B.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004B" title="Positive and negative objects">positive or negative</link>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>17928</anchor> <rss>jms-004F.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-004F</addr>  <route>jms-004F.xml</route> <date><year>2022</year> <month>12</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Preduploid</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A deductive system <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex> is called a <em>preduploid</em> when every object <tex>A \in \mathcal {D}</tex> is <link href="jms-0045.xml" type="local" addr="jms-0045" title="Polarized object">polarized</link>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>17929</anchor> <rss>jms-0050.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-0050</addr>  <route>jms-0050.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Duploid</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A <link href="jms-004F.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004F" title="Preduploid">preduploid</link> <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex> is called a <em>duploid</em> when it satisfies the following properties:</p><ol><li>the preduploid <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex> is <link href="jms-004T.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004T" title="Univalent deductive system">univalent</link>;</li>
  <li>every <link href="jms-004B.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004B" title="Positive and negative objects">positive</link> object of <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex> <link href="jms-004X.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004X" title="Uniqueness of upshifts">has an upshift</link>;</li>
  <li>every <link href="jms-004B.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004B" title="Positive and negative objects">negative</link> object of <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex> <link href="jms-004Z.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004Z" title="Uniqueness of downshifts">has a downshift</link>.</li></ol></mainmatter> </tree></mainmatter> </tree></context> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>17930</anchor> <rss>jms-004P.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-004P</addr>  <route>jms-004P.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Downshift structure</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex> be a <link href="jms-0048.xml" type="local" addr="jms-0048" title="Deductive system">deductive system</link> and let <tex>A</tex> be an object of <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex>. A <em>downshift structure</em> for <tex>A</tex> is defined to be a
  <link href="jms-004B.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004B" title="Positive and negative objects">positive</link> object <tex>\mathord { \Downarrow }  A</tex> and a <link href="jms-004A.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004A" title="Linear and thunkable maps">thunkable</link> map <tex>\mathsf { wrap } _{ A }  : A \vdash \mathord { \Downarrow }  A</tex> for which there exists a <link href="jms-004N.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004N" title="Linear and thunkable inverses">necessarily unique and linear</link> inverse <tex>\mathsf { unwrap } _{ A }  :  \mathord { \Downarrow }  A \vdash  A</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>17931</anchor> <rss>jms-0050.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-0050</addr>  <route>jms-0050.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Duploid</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A <link href="jms-004F.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004F" title="Preduploid">preduploid</link> <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex> is called a <em>duploid</em> when it satisfies the following properties:</p><ol><li>the preduploid <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex> is <link href="jms-004T.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004T" title="Univalent deductive system">univalent</link>;</li>
  <li>every <link href="jms-004B.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004B" title="Positive and negative objects">positive</link> object of <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex> <link href="jms-004X.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004X" title="Uniqueness of upshifts">has an upshift</link>;</li>
  <li>every <link href="jms-004B.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004B" title="Positive and negative objects">negative</link> object of <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex> <link href="jms-004Z.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004Z" title="Uniqueness of downshifts">has a downshift</link>.</li></ol></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>17932</anchor> <rss>jms-004T.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-004T</addr>  <route>jms-004T.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Univalent deductive system</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A <link href="jms-0048.xml" type="local" addr="jms-0048" title="Deductive system">deductive system</link> is called <em>univalent</em> when it is both <link href="jms-004Q.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004Q" title="Positively univalent deductive system">positively univalent</link> and <link href="jms-004S.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004S" title="Negatively univalent deductive system">negatively univalent</link>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>17933</anchor> <rss>jms-004M.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-004M</addr>  <route>jms-004M.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>4</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Upshift structure</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex> be a <link href="jms-0048.xml" type="local" addr="jms-0048" title="Deductive system">deductive system</link> and let <tex>A</tex> be an object of <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex>. An <em>upshift structure</em> for <tex>A</tex> is defined to be a
  <link href="jms-004B.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004B" title="Positive and negative objects">negative</link> object <tex>\mathord { \Uparrow }  A</tex> and a <link href="jms-004A.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004A" title="Linear and thunkable maps">linear</link> map <tex>\mathsf { force } _{ A }  :  \mathord { \Uparrow }  A \vdash  A</tex> for which there exists a <link href="jms-004N.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004N" title="Linear and thunkable inverses">necessarily unique and thunkable</link> inverse <tex>\mathsf { delay } _{ A }  : A \vdash   \mathord { \Uparrow }  A</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>17934</anchor> <rss>jms-0045.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-0045</addr>  <route>jms-0045.xml</route> <date><year>2022</year> <month>12</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Polarized object</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>An object <tex>A</tex> in a deductive system is called <em>polarized</em> when it is either <link href="jms-004B.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004B" title="Positive and negative objects">positive or negative</link>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>17935</anchor> <rss>jms-004B.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-004B</addr>  <route>jms-004B.xml</route> <date><year>2022</year> <month>12</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Positive and negative objects</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>An object <tex>B</tex> in a <link href="jms-0048.xml" type="local" addr="jms-0048" title="Deductive system">deductive system</link> <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex> is called <em>positive</em> when every map <tex>B \vdash  C</tex> is <link href="jms-004A.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004A" title="Linear and thunkable maps">linear</link>; it is called <em>negative</em> when every map <tex>A \vdash  B</tex> is <link href="jms-004A.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004A" title="Linear and thunkable maps">thunkable</link>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>17936</anchor> <rss>jms-004F.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-004F</addr>  <route>jms-004F.xml</route> <date><year>2022</year> <month>12</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Preduploid</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A deductive system <tex>\mathcal {D}</tex> is called a <em>preduploid</em> when every object <tex>A \in \mathcal {D}</tex> is <link href="jms-0045.xml" type="local" addr="jms-0045" title="Polarized object">polarized</link>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></related> <backlinks/> <references/></backmatter></tree>